# **Java Learning Session: From "Hello World" to Object-Oriented Mastery**

## **Session Title:** Foundations of Java: Syntax, Structure & Object-Oriented Principles

---

## **1. Session Overview & Objectives**
**Duration:** 3 Hours  
**Level:** Beginner to Intermediate  
**Tools Required:** JDK 17+, IntelliJ IDEA/Eclipse/VS Code, Notebook

**By the end of this session, learners will be able to:**
- Understand Java's architecture and JVM ecosystem
- Write, compile, and execute Java programs
- Master core syntax: variables, operators, control flow
- Implement basic Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts
- Debug common compilation and runtime errors
- Develop a simple console-based application

---

## **2. Detailed Session Structure**

### **Part 1: Java Ecosystem & Setup (30 mins)**
**A. The Java Universe: JVM, JRE, JDK**
- JVM (Java Virtual Machine): The execution engine
- JRE (Java Runtime Environment): JVM + Libraries
- JDK (Java Development Kit): JRE + Development Tools
- "Write Once, Run Anywhere" philosophy

**B. Hands-On: Environment Verification**
```bash
# Terminal/Command Prompt checks
java --version
javac --version
```

**C. First Java Program: Deconstruction**
```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Java is alive!");
    }
}
```
- **Anatomy:** Class declaration, main method, String[] args, System.out
- **Compilation & Execution:** `javac HelloWorld.java` → `java HelloWorld`

---

### **Part 2: Core Java Syntax (60 mins)**
**A. Variables & Data Types**
- Primitive types: `byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, boolean`
- Reference types: Objects and Arrays
- Type casting: Implicit vs Explicit
- `var` keyword (Java 10+)

**B. Operators Deep Dive**
- Arithmetic: `+, -, *, /, %`
- Relational: `==, !=, >, <, >=, <=`
- Logical: `&&, ||, !`
- Bitwise: `&, |, ^, ~, <<, >>, >>>`
- Ternary: `condition ? value1 : value2`

**C. Control Flow Structures**
```java
// If-Else Ladder
if (score >= 90) grade = 'A';
else if (score >= 80) grade = 'B';

// Switch Expressions (Java 14+)
String dayType = switch(day) {
    case "Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri" -> "Weekday";
    case "Sat", "Sun" -> "Weekend";
    default -> "Invalid";
};

// Loops: for, while, do-while, for-each
int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for(int num : numbers) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
```

**D. Hands-On Exercise: Number Guessing Game**
```java
import java.util.Random;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class GuessingGame {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Random rand = new Random();
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        int target = rand.nextInt(100) + 1;
        int attempts = 0;

        System.out.println("Guess a number between 1-100");

        while(true) {
            System.out.print("Your guess: ");
            int guess = scanner.nextInt();
            attempts++;

            if(guess == target) {
                System.out.printf("Correct! Attempts: %d%n", attempts);
                break;
            } else if(guess < target) {
                System.out.println("Too low!");
            } else {
                System.out.println("Too high!");
            }
        }
        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

---

### **Part 3: Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming (75 mins)**
**A. The Four Pillars of OOP**
1. **Encapsulation:** Data hiding with private fields + public methods
2. **Inheritance:** `extends` keyword, superclass/subclass relationships
3. **Polymorphism:** Method overriding + interface implementations
4. **Abstraction:** Abstract classes vs Interfaces

**B. Class & Object Implementation**
```java
// Complete Example: Bank Account System
public class BankAccount {
    // Encapsulation: private fields
    private String accountNumber;
    private double balance;
    private String accountHolder;

    // Constructor
    public BankAccount(String accountHolder, String accountNumber) {
        this.accountHolder = accountHolder;
        this.accountNumber = accountNumber;
        this.balance = 0.0;
    }

    // Public methods (interface)
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if(amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
            System.out.printf("Deposited: $%.2f%n", amount);
        }
    }

    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if(amount > 0 && balance >= amount) {
            balance -= amount;
            System.out.printf("Withdrawn: $%.2f%n", amount);
            return true;
        }
        System.out.println("Insufficient funds!");
        return false;
    }

    // Getter (read-only access)
    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return String.format("Account[Holder: %s, Balance: $%.2f]", 
                           accountHolder, balance);
    }
}
```

**C. Inheritance & Polymorphism Example**
```java
// Base class
abstract class Vehicle {
    protected String brand;

    public Vehicle(String brand) {
        this.brand = brand;
    }

    abstract void start(); // Abstract method

    public void displayBrand() {
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand);
    }
}

// Derived class
class Car extends Vehicle {
    private int doors;

    public Car(String brand, int doors) {
        super(brand); // Call parent constructor
        this.doors = doors;
    }

    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println("Car engine starting...");
    }

    // Additional method
    public void displayDoors() {
        System.out.println("Number of doors: " + doors);
    }
}

// Usage
Vehicle myCar = new Car("Toyota", 4);
myCar.start(); // Polymorphic call
```

